The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Bail for boy

 New Delhi, Dec, 24: Indian Institute of Technology student Ravi Raj, accused of selling a sexually explicit video clip involving two minor students of a Delhi school, has been granted bail by a local court, reports our correspondent.

 Observing that the prime accused in the case have already been released on bail, additional sessions judge Aruna Suresh granted bail to Raj, who put up the clip for sale at Rs 125 on baazee.com, India?s largest online trading portal.

 Raj, a student of the five-year integrated MSc programme in exploration geophysics at IIT Kharagpur, was ordered to furnish a personal bond of Rs 50,000 and two sureties of like amount. The 23-year-old was also directed not to leave the country, to surrender his passport, cooperate with the investigating agencies and not try to influence witnesses.

 Raj was arrested by Delhi police on December 14 after it took cognisance of media reports that the slip was being sold on the portal.

 With the help of baazee.com employees, Delhi police?s economic offences wing traced the student to the IIT Kharagpur campus. 

 It tracked down the online transactions of Alice Electronics, Raj?s company that had taken up space with the portal and put the clip up for auction. The clip was put up on November 27 and remained there for two days. 




